This dataset contains marital status by age for customers targeted in a bankâs marketing campaign taken from UC Irvineâs Machine Learning Repository.

â Click the link below to download the dataset for this worksheet to your hard drive.

bank_customer_marital_status.csv

This chart is a histogram (not a bar or column chart)! You make a histogram in worksheet 4.

The histogram bins are each 2-years wide.

The colours for the chart are #974B4B, #867FA4, and #040404. To find hex values for different colours you can Google one of these hex values to get a colour picker tool.

Show the code 
# READ IN -----------------------------------------------------------------

data_raw <-
  readr::read_csv(file = "bank_customer_marital_status.csv")


# VISUALISE ---------------------------------------------------------------

my_plot <-
  data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = age,
                                         fill = marital_status)) +
  ggplot2::geom_histogram(colour = "white",
                          binwidth = 2) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10),
                              limits = c(0, 100)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma()) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("Single" = "#974B4B", "Married" = "#867FA4", "Divorced" = "#040404")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ~marital_status,
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::labs(x = "Age (years)",
                y = "Count") +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot2::ggsave(filename = "bank_marital_status.png",
                plot = my_plot,
                dpi = 300,
                units = "mm",
                height = 180,
                width = 125)
